eed to expunge to move forward. To try and 'prove' that this is a country built somehow on the premise of 'religion' is a falsehood. The fact that religious missionaries were able to force their cult dogmas onto both immigrant and native populations is unfortunate enough - we don't need to perpetuate that unhappy circumstance at inifinitum. Canada does not 'owe' religion any debt, although the reverse may be true. &#10;If we're going to drag that out from the past, better we honor the views the REAL founders of this country - the native &quot;Indians&quot;. We'd be honouring our families, elders, have a culture of pride, respect nature and protect the land a lot more. &#10;It's time to let go of the notion that religious people, and in Canada that means primarily Christians, have MORE rights than others. The 'Rights and Charters' aimed to protect individual rights and freedoms - not to extend the 'right' for individuals to force their views on others. &#10;By all means, pray if you must. But why do you feel the need to involve others in that? As b.c.Terry suggested, that's rude and intrusive. I'll add presumptious and unwelcome. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1418" language="en" documentId="1215" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="ZeeBeeSee" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1215" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="84"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="85" end="711"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="712" end="956"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="957" end="1241"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="1242" end="1418"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>